# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: zig
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Zig is a general-purpose programming language and toolchain for maintaining **robust**, **optimal**, and **reusable** software.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Behavior is correct even for edge cases such as out of memory.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Write programs the best way they can behave and perform.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The same code works in many environments which have different constraints.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Precisely communicate intent to the compiler and other programmers.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The language imposes a low overhead to reading code and is resilient to changing requirements and environments.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Often the most efficient way to learn something new is to see examples, so this documentation shows how to use each of Zig's features.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] It is all on one page so you can search with your browser's search tool.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The code samples in this document are compiled and tested as part of the main test suite of Zig.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] This HTML document depends on no external files, so you can use it offline.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The Zig Standard Library has its own documentation.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Zig's Standard Library contains commonly used algorithms, data structures, and definitions to help you build programs or libraries.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] You will see many examples of Zig's Standard Library used in this documentation.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] To learn more about the Zig Standard Library, visit the link above.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Alternatively, the Zig Standard Library documentation is provided with each Zig distribution.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Most of the time, it is more appropriate to write to stderr rather than stdout, and whether or not the message is successfully written to the stream is irrelevant.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Also, formatted printing often comes in handy.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] In this case, the `!` may be omitted from the return type of `main` because no errors are returned from the function.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Normal comments are ignored, while Doc Comments and Top-Level Doc Comments are used by the compiler to generate the package documentation.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Zig has the property that each line of code can be tokenized independently.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] A doc comment is one that begins with exactly three slashes (i.e. but not ); multiple doc comments in a row are merged together to form a multiline doc comment.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The doc comment documents whatever immediately follows it.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Doc comments are only allowed in certain places; it is a compile error to have a doc comment in an unexpected place, such as in the middle of an expression, or just before a non-doc comment.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Doc comments can be interleaved with normal comments, which are ignored.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] A top-level doc comment is one that begins with two slashes and an exclamation point: ; it documents the type which owns the containing Namespace.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] It is a compile error if a top-level doc comment is not placed at the start of a namespace, before any expressions.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] A namespace in Zig is created by struct, enum, union, and opaque.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] They contain Namespace Level Variables, function declarations, and comptime blocks.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Although namespaces use curly braces to surround their definition, they should not be confused with blocks or function bodies.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Identifiers must start with an alphabetic character or underscore and may be followed by any number of alphanumeric characters or underscores.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] They must not overlap with any keywords.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] If a name that does not fit these requirements is needed, such as for linking with external libraries, the `@""` syntax may be used.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] In addition to the integer types above, arbitrary bit-width integers can be referenced by using an identifier of `i` or `u` followed by digits.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] For example, the identifier `i7` refers to a signed 7-bit integer.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The maximum allowed bit-width of an integer type is `65535`.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] String literals are constant single-item Pointers to null-terminated byte arrays.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The type of string literals encodes both the length, and the fact that they are null-terminated, and thus they can be coerced to both Slices and Null-Terminated Pointers.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Dereferencing string literals converts them to Arrays.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Because Zig source code is UTF-8 encoded, any non-ASCII bytes appearing within a string literal in source code carry their UTF-8 meaning into the content of the string in the Zig program; the bytes are not modified by the compiler.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] It is possible to embed non-UTF-8 bytes into a string literal using `\xNN` notation.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Indexing into a string containing non-ASCII bytes returns individual bytes, whether valid UTF-8 or not.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Unicode code point literals have type `comptime_int`, the same as Integer Literals.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] All Escape Sequences are valid in both string literals and Unicode code point literals.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Note that the maximum valid Unicode scalar value is `0x10ffff`.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Multiline string literals have no escapes and can span across multiple lines.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] To start a multiline string literal, use the `\\` token.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Just like a comment, the string literal goes until the end of the line.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The end of the line is not included in the string literal.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] However, if the next line begins with `\\` then a newline is appended and the string literal continues.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] `const` applies to all of the bytes that the identifier immediately addresses.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Once this happens, it is no longer possible to detect that the value is `undefined`.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] `undefined` means the value could be anything, even something that is nonsense according to the type.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Translated into English, `undefined` means "Not a meaningful value.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] In Debug and ReleaseSafe mode, Zig writes `0xaa` bytes to undefined memory.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] This is to catch bugs early, and to help detect use of undefined memory in a debugger.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] However, this behavior is only an implementation feature, not a language semantic, so it is not guaranteed to be observable to code.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] A destructuring expression may only appear within a block (i.e. not at Namespace scope).
[src:zig/documentation-p01] A destructure may be prefixed with the `comptime` keyword, in which case the entire destructure expression is evaluated at comptime.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] All `var`s declared would be `comptime var`s and all expressions (both result locations and the assignee expression) are evaluated at comptime.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The `testing_introduction.zig` code sample tests the function `addOne` to ensure that it returns `42` given the input `41`.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] From this test's perspective, the `addOne` function is said to be *code under test*.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] zig test is a tool that creates and runs a test build.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] By default, it builds and runs an executable program using the *default test runner* provided by the Zig Standard Library as its main entry point.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] During the build, `test` declarations found while resolving the given Zig source file are included for the default test runner to run and report on.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The shell output shown above displays two lines after the zig test command.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Lines like this indicate which test, out of the total number of tests, is being run.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] indicates that the first test, out of a total of two tests, is being run.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Note that, when the test runner program's standard error is output to the terminal, these lines are cleared when a test succeeds.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] When the test name is an identifier, the default test runner uses the text decltest instead of test.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] This line indicates the total number of tests that have passed.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Test declarations contain the keyword `test`, followed by an optional name written as a string literal or an identifier, followed by a block containing any valid Zig code that is allowed in a function.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Non-named test blocks always run during test builds and are exempt from Skip Tests.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Test declarations are similar to Functions: they have a return type and a block of code.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The implicit return type of `test` is the Error Union Type `anyerror!void`, and it cannot be changed.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] When a Zig source file is not built using the zig test tool, the test declarations are omitted from the build.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Test declarations can be written in the same file, where code under test is written, or in a separate Zig source file.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Since test declarations are top-level declarations, they are order-independent and can be written before or after the code under test.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Test declarations named using an identifier are *doctests*.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The identifier must refer to another declaration in scope.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] A doctest, like a doc comment, serves as documentation for the associated declaration, and will appear in the generated documentation for the declaration.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] An effective doctest should be self-contained and focused on the declaration being tested, answering questions a new user might have about its interface or intended usage, while avoiding unnecessary or confusing details.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] A doctest is not a substitute for a doc comment, but rather a supplement and companion providing a testable, code-driven example, verified by zig test.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The default test runner checks for an error returned from a test.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] When a test returns an error, the test is considered a failure and its error return trace is output to standard error.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The total number of failures will be reported after all tests have run.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] One way to skip tests is to filter them out by using the zig test command line parameter --test-filter [text].
[src:zig/documentation-p01] This makes the test build only include tests whose name contains the supplied filter text.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Note that non-named tests are run even when using the --test-filter [text] command line parameter.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] To programmatically skip a test, make a `test` return the error `error.SkipZigTest` and the default test runner will consider the test as being skipped.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The total number of skipped tests will be reported after all tests have run.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The default test runner and the Zig Standard Library's testing namespace output messages to standard error.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The Zig Standard Library's `testing` namespace contains useful functions to help you create tests.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The Zig Standard Library also contains functions to compare Slices, strings, and more.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] See the rest of the `std.testing` namespace in the Zig Standard Library for more available functions.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] zig test has a few command line parameters which affect the compilation.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] It is generally preferable to use `const` rather than `var` when declaring a variable.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] This causes less work for both humans and computers to do when reading code, and creates more optimization opportunities.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Variables are never allowed to shadow Identifiers from an outer scope.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The `extern` keyword or @extern builtin function can be used to link against a variable that is exported from another object.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The `export` keyword or @export builtin function can be used to make a variable available to other objects at link time.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] In both cases, the type of the variable must be C ABI compatible.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Namespace level variables have global lifetime and are order-independent and lazily analyzed.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The initialization value of namespace level variables is implicitly comptime.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] If a namespace level variable is `const` then its value is `comptime`-known, otherwise it is runtime-known.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] It is also possible to have local variables with global lifetime by using namespaces inside functions.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] For Single Threaded Builds, all thread local variables are treated as regular Namespace Level Variables.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Thread local variables may not be `const`.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Local variables occur inside Functions, comptime blocks, and labeled Blocks.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] When a local variable is `const`, it means that after initialization, the variable's value will not change.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] If the initialization value of a `const` variable is comptime-known, then the variable is also `comptime`-known.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] A local variable may be qualified with the `comptime` keyword.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] This causes the variable's value to be `comptime`-known, and all loads and stores of the variable to happen during semantic analysis of the program, rather than at runtime.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] All variables declared in a `comptime` expression are implicitly `comptime` variables.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Integer literals have no size limitation, and if any Illegal Behavior occurs, the compiler catches it.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] However, once an integer value is no longer known at compile-time, it must have a known size, and is vulnerable to safety-checked Illegal Behavior.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] In this function, values `a` and `b` are known only at runtime, and thus this division operation is vulnerable to both Integer Overflow and Division by Zero.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Operators such as `+` and `-` cause Illegal Behavior on integer overflow.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Alternative operators are provided for wrapping and saturating arithmetic on all targets.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] `+%` and `-%` perform wrapping arithmetic while `+|` and `-|` perform saturating arithmetic.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Zig supports arbitrary bit-width integers, referenced by using an identifier of `i` or `u` followed by digits.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] For signed integer types, Zig uses a two's complement representation.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Float literals have type `comptime_float` which is guaranteed to have the same precision and operations of the largest other floating point type, which is `f128`.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] Float literals coerce to any floating point type, and to any integer type when there is no fractional component.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] There is no syntax for NaN, infinity, or negative infinity.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] For this test we have to separate code into two object files - otherwise the optimizer figures out all the values at compile-time, which operates in strict mode.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] When you see an operator in Zig, you know that it is doing something from this table, and nothing else.
[src:zig/documentation-p01] The syntax `[N:x]T` describes an array which has a sentinel element of value `x` at the index corresponding to the length `N`.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] A vector is a group of booleans, Integers, Floats, or Pointers which are operated on in parallel, using SIMD instructions if possible.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Vector types are created with the builtin function @Vector.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Vectors generally support the same builtin operators as their underlying base types.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] The only exception to this is the keywords `and` and `or` on vectors of bools, since these operators affect control flow, which is not allowed for vectors.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] All other operations are performed element-wise, and return a vector of the same length as the input vectors.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] It is prohibited to use a math operator on a mixture of scalars (individual numbers) and vectors.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Zig provides the @splat builtin to easily convert from scalars to vectors, and it supports @reduce and array indexing syntax to convert from vectors to scalars.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Vectors also support assignment to and from fixed-length arrays with comptime-known length.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] For rearranging elements within and between vectors, Zig provides the @shuffle and @select functions.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Operations on vectors shorter than the target machine's native SIMD size will typically compile to single SIMD instructions, while vectors longer than the target machine's native SIMD size will compile to multiple SIMD instructions.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] If a given operation doesn't have SIMD support on the target architecture, the compiler will default to operating on each vector element one at a time.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Zig supports any comptime-known vector length up to 2^32-1, although small powers of two (2-64) are most typical.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Note that excessively long vector lengths (e.g.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] 2^20) may result in compiler crashes on current versions of Zig.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Vectors and Arrays each have a well-defined **bit layout** and therefore support @bitCast between each other.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Type Coercion implicitly peforms `@bitCast`.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Arrays have well-defined byte layout, but vectors do not, making @ptrCast between them Illegal Behavior.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Zig has two kinds of pointers: single-item and many-item.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] It's better to assign the pointer to `[*]T` and increment that variable.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] For example, directly incrementing the pointer from a slice will corrupt it.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] In Zig, we generally prefer Slices rather than Sentinel-Terminated Pointers.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] You can turn an array or pointer into a slice using slice syntax.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Slices have bounds checking and are therefore protected against this kind of Illegal Behavior.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] This is one reason we prefer slices to pointers.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] To convert an integer address into a pointer, use `@ptrFromInt`.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] @ptrCast converts a pointer's element type to another.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] This creates a new pointer that can cause undetectable Illegal Behavior depending on the loads and stores that pass through it.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Generally, other kinds of type conversions are preferable to `@ptrCast` if possible.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Loads and stores are assumed to not have side effects.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] If a given load or store should have side effects, such as Memory Mapped Input/Output (MMIO), use `volatile`.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Note that `volatile` is unrelated to concurrency and Atomics.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] If you see code that is using `volatile` for something other than Memory Mapped Input/Output, it is probably a bug.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Each type has an **alignment** - a number of bytes such that, when a value of the type is loaded from or stored to memory, the memory address must be evenly divisible by this number.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] You can use @alignOf to find out this value for any type.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Alignment depends on the CPU architecture, but is always a power of two, and less than `1 << 29`.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Pointer types may explicitly specify an alignment in bytes.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] If it is not specified, the alignment is assumed to be equal to the alignment of the underlying type.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] In the same way that a `*i32` can be coerced to a `*const i32`, a pointer with a larger alignment can be implicitly cast to a pointer with a smaller alignment, but not vice versa.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] You can specify alignment on variables and functions.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] If you have a pointer or a slice that has a small alignment, but you know that it actually has a bigger alignment, use @alignCast to change the pointer into a more aligned pointer.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] This pointer attribute allows a pointer to have address zero.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] This is only ever needed on the freestanding OS target, where the address zero is mappable.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] If you want to represent null pointers, use Optional Pointers instead.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Optional Pointers with `allowzero` are not the same size as pointers.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] The syntax `[*:x]T` describes a pointer that has a length determined by a sentinel value.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] This provides protection against buffer overflow and overreads.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] The difference between an array and a slice is that the array's length is part of the type and known at compile-time, whereas the slice's length is known at runtime.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Both can be accessed with the `len` field.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Even though Zig only has syntax for slicing based on start and end indices, by slicing twice, one can express a **slice by length** operation.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] The syntax `[:x]T` is a slice which has a runtime-known length and also guarantees a sentinel value at the element indexed by the length.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] The type does not guarantee that there are no sentinel elements before that.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Sentinel-terminated slices allow element access to the `len` index.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Sentinel-terminated slices can also be created using a variation of the slice syntax `data[start..end :x]`, where `data` is a many-item pointer, array or slice and `x` is the sentinel value.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Sentinel-terminated slicing asserts that the element in the sentinel position of the backing data is actually the sentinel value.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] If this is not the case, safety-checked Illegal Behavior results.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Each struct field may have an expression indicating the default field value.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Default field values are only appropriate when the data invariants of a struct cannot be violated by omitting that field from an initialization.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Above you can see the danger of ignoring this principle.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] The default field values caused the data invariant to be violated, causing illegal behavior.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] If a struct value requires a runtime-known value in order to be initialized without violating data invariants, then use an initialization method that accepts those runtime values, and populates the remaining fields.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] An `extern struct` has in-memory layout matching the C ABI for the target.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] If well-defined in-memory layout is not required, struct is a better choice because it places fewer restrictions on the compiler.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] See packed struct for a struct that has the ABI of its backing integer, which can be useful for modeling flags.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] `packed` structs, like `enum`, are based on the concept of interpreting integers differently.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] All packed structs have a **backing integer**, which is implicitly determined by the total bit count of fields, or explicitly specified.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Packed structs have well-defined memory layout - exactly the same ABI as their backing integer.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Each field of a packed struct is interpreted as a logical sequence of bits, arranged from least to most significant.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] This means that a `packed struct` can participate in a @bitCast or a @ptrCast to reinterpret memory.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] The backing integer can be inferred or explicitly provided.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] In this case, the function `bar` cannot be called because the pointer to the non-ABI-aligned field mentions the bit offset, but the function expects an ABI-aligned pointer.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Equating packed structs results in a comparison of the backing integer, and only works for the `==` and `!=` Operators.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Field access and assignment can be understood as shorthand for bitshifts on the backing integer.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] These operations are not atomic, so beware using field access syntax when combined with memory-mapped input-output (MMIO).
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Instead of field access on volatile Pointers, construct a fully-formed new value first, then write that value to the volatile pointer.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Since all structs are anonymous, Zig infers the type name based on a few rules.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Zig allows omitting the struct type of a literal.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Anonymous structs can be created without specifying field names, and are referred to as "tuples".
[src:zig/documentation-p02] An empty tuple looks like `.{}` and can be seen in one of the Hello World examples.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] The fields are implicitly named using numbers starting from 0.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Because their names are integers, they cannot be accessed with `.` syntax without also wrapping them in `@""`.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Names inside `@""` are always recognised as identifiers.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] Like arrays, tuples have a .len field, can be indexed (provided the index is comptime-known) and work with the ++ operator.
[src:zig/documentation-p02] They can also be iterated over with inline for.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] A non-exhaustive enum can be created by adding a trailing `_` field.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] The enum must specify a tag type and cannot consume every enumeration value.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] @enumFromInt on a non-exhaustive enum involves the safety semantics of @intCast to the integer tag type, but beyond that always results in a well-defined enum value.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] A switch on a non-exhaustive enum can include a `_` prong as an alternative to an `else` prong.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] With a `_` prong the compiler errors if all the known tag names are not handled by the switch.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] A bare `union` defines a set of possible types that a value can be as a list of fields.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] The in-memory representation of bare unions is not guaranteed.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Bare unions cannot be used to reinterpret memory.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] For that, use @ptrCast, or use an extern union or a packed union which have guaranteed in-memory layout.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] In order to use switch with a union, it must be a Tagged union.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] To initialize a union when the tag is a comptime-known name, see @unionInit.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Unions can be declared with an enum tag type.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] This turns the union into a *tagged* union, which makes it eligible to use with switch expressions.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] When switching on tagged unions, the tag value can be obtained using an additional capture.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Tagged unions coerce to their tag type: Type Coercion: Unions and Enums.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Unions can be made to infer the enum tag type.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Further, unions can have methods just like structs and enums.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Unions with inferred enum tag types can also assign ordinal values to their inferred tag.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] This requires the tag to specify an explicit integer type. @intFromEnum can be used to access the ordinal value corresponding to the active field.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] An `extern union` has memory layout guaranteed to be compatible with the target C ABI.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] A `packed union` has well-defined in-memory layout and is eligible to be in a packed struct.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] All fields in a packed union must have the same @bitSizeOf.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Equating packed unions results in a comparison of the backing integer, and only works for the `==` and `!=` Operators.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] `opaque {}` declares a new type with an unknown (but non-zero) size and alignment.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] It can contain declarations the same as structs, unions, and enums.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] This is typically used for type safety when interacting with C code that does not expose struct details.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Because of this, when you read Zig code you can always rely on an identifier to consistently mean the same thing within the scope it is defined.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] `switch` can be used to capture the field values of a Tagged union.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Modifications to the field values can be done by placing a `*` before the capture variable name, turning it into a pointer.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] When a `switch` expression does not have an `else` clause, it must exhaustively list all the possible values.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] When a switch statement is labeled, it can be referenced from a `break` or `continue`.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] `break` will return a value from the `switch`.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] A `continue` targeting a switch must have an operand.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] When executed, it will jump to the matching prong, as if the `switch` were executed again with the `continue`'s operand replacing the initial switch value.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] This can improve clarity of (for example) state machines, where the syntax `continue :sw .next_state` is unambiguous, explicit, and immediately understandable.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] If the operand to `continue` is comptime-known, then it can be lowered to an unconditional branch to the relevant case.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Such a branch is perfectly predicted, and hence typically very fast to execute.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] If the operand is runtime-known, each `continue` can embed a conditional branch inline (ideally through a jump table), which allows a CPU to predict its target independently of any other prong.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] A loop-based lowering would force every branch through the same dispatch point, hindering branch prediction.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Switch prongs can be marked as `inline` to generate the prong's body for each possible value it could have, making the captured value comptime.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] When using an inline prong switching on an union an additional capture can be used to obtain the union's enum tag value at comptime, even though its payload might only be known at runtime.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] A while loop is used to repeatedly execute an expression until some condition is no longer true.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Use `continue` to jump back to the beginning of the loop.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] While loops support a continue expression which is executed when the loop is continued.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] The `continue` keyword respects this expression.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] The result of the expression is the result of the `else` clause of a while loop, which is executed when the condition of the while loop is tested as false.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] `break`, like `return`, accepts a value parameter.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] This is the result of the `while` expression.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] When you `break` from a while loop, the `else` branch is not evaluated.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Just like if expressions, while loops can take an optional as the condition and capture the payload.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] When null is encountered the loop exits.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] When the `|x|` syntax is present on a `while` expression, the while condition must have an Optional Type.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] The `else` branch is allowed on optional iteration.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] In this case, it will be executed on the first null value encountered.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Just like if expressions, while loops can take an error union as the condition and capture the payload or the error code.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] When the condition results in an error code the else branch is evaluated and the loop is finished.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] When the `else |x|` syntax is present on a `while` expression, the while condition must have an Error Union Type.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] This causes the loop to be unrolled, which allows the code to do some things which only work at compile time, such as use types as first class values.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] The capture value and iterator value of inlined for loops are compile-time known.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Executes an expression unconditionally at scope exit.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Defer expressions are evaluated in reverse order.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] Inside a defer expression the return statement is not allowed.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] In Debug and ReleaseSafe mode `unreachable` emits a call to `panic` with the message `reached unreachable code`.
[src:zig/documentation-p03] In ReleaseFast and ReleaseSmall mode, the optimizer uses the assumption that `unreachable` code will never be hit to perform optimizations.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] When resolving types together, such as `if` clauses or `switch` prongs, the `noreturn` type is compatible with every other type.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] There is a difference between a function *body* and a function *pointer*.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Function bodies are comptime-only types while function Pointers may be runtime-known.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Primitive types such as Integers and Floats passed as parameters are copied, and then the copy is available in the function body.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Copying a primitive type is essentially free and typically involves nothing more than setting a register.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Structs, unions, and arrays can sometimes be more efficiently passed as a reference, since a copy could be arbitrarily expensive depending on the size.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] When these types are passed as parameters, Zig may choose to copy and pass by value, or pass by reference, whichever way Zig decides will be faster.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] This is made possible, in part, by the fact that parameters are immutable.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] For extern functions, Zig follows the C ABI for passing structs and unions by value.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Function parameters can be declared with `anytype` in place of the type.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] In this case the parameter types will be inferred when the function is called.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Use @TypeOf and @typeInfo to get information about the inferred type.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Adding the `inline` keyword to a function definition makes that function become *semantically inlined* at the callsite.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] This is not a hint to be possibly observed by optimization passes, but has implications on the types and values involved in the function call.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Unlike normal function calls, arguments at an inline function callsite which are compile-time known are treated as Compile Time Parameters.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] If `inline` is removed, the test fails with the compile error instead of passing.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Note that `inline` actually *restricts* what the compiler is allowed to do.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] This can harm binary size, compilation speed, and even runtime performance.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] However, each error name across the entire compilation gets assigned an unsigned integer greater than 0.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] You are allowed to declare the same error name more than once, and if you do, it gets assigned the same integer value.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The error set type defaults to a `u16`, though if the maximum number of distinct error values is provided via the --error-limit [num] command line parameter an integer type with the minimum number of bits required to represent all of the error values will be used.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] This becomes useful when using Inferred Error Sets.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] `anyerror` refers to the global error set.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] This is the error set that contains all errors in the entire compilation unit, i.e. it is the union of all other error sets.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] You can coerce any error set to the global one, and you can explicitly cast an error of the global error set to a non-global one.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] This inserts a language-level assert to make sure the error value is in fact in the destination error set.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The global error set should generally be avoided because it prevents the compiler from knowing what errors are possible at compile-time.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Knowing the error set at compile-time is better for generated documentation and helpful error messages, such as forgetting a possible error value in a switch.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] An error set type and normal type can be combined with the `!` binary operator to form an error union type.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] You are likely to use an error union type more often than an error set type by itself.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] This means that the function either returns an unsigned 64 bit integer, or an error.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] We left off the error set to the left of the `!`, so the error set is inferred.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Within the function definition, you can see some return statements that return an error, and at the bottom a return statement that returns a `u64`.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] What it looks like to use this function varies depending on what you're trying to do.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] In this code, `number` will be equal to the successfully parsed string, or a default value of 13.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The type of the right hand side of the binary `catch` operator must match the unwrapped error union type, or be of type `noreturn`.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] `try` evaluates an error union expression.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] If it is an error, it returns from the current function with the same error.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Otherwise, the expression results in the unwrapped value.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Maybe you know with complete certainty that an expression will never be an error.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Here we know for sure that "1234" will parse successfully.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] So we put the `unreachable` value on the right hand side.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] `unreachable` invokes safety-checked Illegal Behavior, so in Debug and ReleaseSafe, triggers a safety panic by default.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] So, while we're debugging the application, if there *was* a surprise error here, the application would crash appropriately.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] You may want to take a different action for every situation.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Finally, you may want to handle only some errors.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] You must use the variable capture syntax.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] If you don't need the variable, you can capture with `_` and avoid the `switch`.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The other component to error handling is defer statements.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] In addition to an unconditional defer, Zig has `errdefer`, which evaluates the deferred expression on block exit path if and only if the function returned with an error from the block.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The neat thing about this is that you get robust error handling without the verbosity and cognitive overhead of trying to make sure every exit path is covered.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The deallocation code is always directly following the allocation code.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] An error union is created with the `!` binary operator.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Use the `||` operator to merge two error sets together.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The resulting error set contains the errors of both error sets.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Doc comments from the left-hand side override doc comments from the right-hand side.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] In this example, the doc comments for `C.PathNotFound` is `A doc comment`.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] This is especially useful for functions which return different error sets depending on comptime branches.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] For example, the Zig standard library uses `LinuxFileOpenError || WindowsFileOpenError` for the error set of opening files.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Because many functions in Zig return a possible error, Zig supports inferring the error set.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] When a function has an inferred error set, that function becomes generic and thus it becomes trickier to do certain things with it, such as obtain a function pointer, or have an error set that is consistent across different build targets.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Additionally, inferred error sets are incompatible with recursion.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] In these situations, it is recommended to use an explicit error set.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] You can generally start with an empty error set and let compile errors guide you toward completing the set.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] These limitations may be overcome in a future version of Zig.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Error Return Traces show all the points in the code that an error was returned to the calling function.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] This makes it practical to use try everywhere and then still be able to know what happened if an error ends up bubbling all the way out of your application.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] You can see that the final error bubbled up was `PermissionDenied`, but the original error that started this whole thing was `FileNotFound`.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] In the `bar` function, the code handles the original error code, and then returns another one, from the switch statement.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Here, the stack trace does not explain how the control flow in `bar` got to the `hello()` call.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] One would have to open a debugger or further instrument the application in order to find out.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The error return trace, on the other hand, shows exactly how the error bubbled up.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] This debugging feature makes it easier to iterate quickly on code that robustly handles all error conditions.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] This means that Zig developers will naturally find themselves writing correct, robust code in order to increase their development pace.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Error Return Traces are enabled by default in Debug builds and disabled by default in ReleaseFast, ReleaseSafe and ReleaseSmall builds.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] For the case when no errors are returned, the cost is a single memory write operation, only in the first non-failable function in the call graph that calls a failable function, i.e. when a function returning `void` calls a function returning `error`.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Here, N is the maximum function call depth as determined by call graph analysis.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] A pointer to `StackTrace` is passed as a secret parameter to every function that can return an error, but it's always the first parameter, so it can likely sit in a register and stay there.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] That's it for the path when no errors occur.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] It's practically free in terms of performance.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The cost is 2 math operations plus some memory reads and writes.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The memory accessed is constrained and should remain cached for the duration of the error return bubbling.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] As for code size cost, 1 function call before a return statement is no big deal.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Even so, I have a plan to make the call to `__zig_return_error` a tail call, which brings the code size cost down to actually zero.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] What is a return statement in code without error return tracing can become a jump instruction in code with error return tracing.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] One area that Zig provides safety without compromising efficiency or readability is with the optional type.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The question mark symbolizes the optional type.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Now the variable `optional_int` could be an `i32`, or `null`.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Instead of integers, let's talk about pointers.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Null references are the source of many runtime exceptions, and even stand accused of being the worst mistake of computer science.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Instead, you can use an optional pointer.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] This secretly compiles down to a normal pointer, since we know we can use 0 as the null value for the optional type.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] But the compiler can check your work and make sure you don't assign null to something that can't be null.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Typically the downside of not having null is that it makes the code more verbose to write.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] But, let's compare some equivalent C code and Zig code.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Task: call malloc, if the result is null, return null.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Here, Zig is at least as convenient, if not more, than C.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The `orelse` keyword unwrapped the optional type and therefore `ptr` is guaranteed to be non-null everywhere it is used in the function.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Once again, the notable thing here is that inside the if block, `foo` is no longer an optional pointer, it is a pointer, which cannot be null.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] One benefit to this is that functions which take pointers as arguments can be annotated with the "nonnull" attribute - `__attribute__((nonnull))` in GCC.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The optimizer can sometimes make better decisions knowing that pointer arguments cannot be null.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] An optional is created by putting `?` in front of a type.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] An optional pointer is guaranteed to be the same size as a pointer.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The `null` of the optional is guaranteed to be address 0.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] A **type cast** converts a value of one type to another.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Zig has Type Coercion for conversions that are known to be completely safe and unambiguous, and Explicit Casts for conversions that one would not want to happen on accident.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] There is also a third kind of type conversion called Peer Type Resolution for the case when a result type must be decided given multiple operand types.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Type coercions are only allowed when it is completely unambiguous how to get from one type to another, and the transformation is guaranteed to be safe.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] There is one exception, which is C Pointers.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] These casts are no-ops at runtime since the value representation does not change.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Integers coerce to integer types which can represent every value of the old type, and likewise Floats coerce to float types which can represent every value of the old type.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Integers coerce to Floats if every possible integer value can be stored in the float without rounding (i.e. the integer's precision does not exceed the float's significand precision).
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Larger integer types that cannot be safely coerced must be explicitly casted with @floatFromInt.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] A compiler error is appropriate because this ambiguous expression leaves the compiler two choices about the coercion.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] The payload type of Optionals, as well as null, coerce to the optional type.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Tuples can be coerced to arrays, if all of the fields have the same type.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Explicit casts are performed via Builtin Functions.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Some explicit casts can violate type safety when used incorrectly.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Some explicit casts perform language-level assertions.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] Some explicit casts are no-ops at runtime.
[src:zig/documentation-p04] This kind of type resolution chooses a type that all peer types can coerce into.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] These types can only ever have one possible value, and thus require 0 bits to represent.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] When this turns into machine code, there is no code generated in the body of `entry`, even in Debug mode.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] These assembly instructions do not have any code associated with the void values - they only perform the function call prologue and epilogue.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] `void` can be useful for instantiating generic types.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Note that this is different from using a dummy value for the hash map value.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] By using `void` as the type of the value, the hash map entry type has no value field, and thus the hash map takes up less space.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Further, all the code that deals with storing and loading the value is deleted, as seen above.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] `void` has a known size of 0 bytes, and `anyopaque` has an unknown, but non-zero, size.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Expressions of type `void` are the only ones whose value can be ignored.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] However, if the expression has type `void`, there will be no error.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Expression results can be explicitly ignored by assigning them to `_`.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] During compilation, every Zig expression and sub-expression is assigned optional result location information.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This information dictates what type the expression should have (its result type), and where the resulting value should be placed in memory (its result location).
[src:zig/documentation-p05] The information is optional in the sense that not every expression has this information: assignment to `_`, for instance, does not provide any information about the type of an expression, nor does it provide a concrete memory location to place it in.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] As a motivating example, consider the statement `const x: u32 = 42;`.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] The type annotation here provides a result type of `u32` to the initialization expression `42`, instructing the compiler to coerce this integer (initially of type `comptime_int`) to this type.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This is not an implementation detail: the logic outlined above is codified into the Zig language specification, and is the primary mechanism of type inference in the language.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This system is collectively referred to as "Result Location Semantics".
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Result types are propagated recursively through expressions where possible.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] For instance, if the expression `&e` has result type `*u32`, then `e` is given a result type of `u32`, allowing the language to perform this coercion before taking a reference.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] The result type mechanism is utilized by casting builtins such as `@intCast`.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Rather than taking as an argument the type to cast to, these builtins use their result type to determine this information.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] The result type is often known from context; where it is not, the `@as` builtin can be used to explicitly provide a result type.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This result type information is useful for the aforementioned cast builtins, as well as to avoid the construction of pre-coercion values, and to avoid the need for explicit type coercions in some cases.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] The following table details how some common expressions propagate result types, where `x` and `y` are arbitrary sub-expressions.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] In addition to result type information, every expression may be optionally assigned a result location: a pointer to which the value must be directly written.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This system can be used to prevent intermediate copies when initializing data structures, which can be important for types which must have a fixed memory address ("pinned" types).
[src:zig/documentation-p05] When compiling the simple assignment expression `x = e`, many languages would create the temporary value `e` on the stack, and then assign it to `x`, potentially performing a type coercion in the process.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] The expression `e` is given a result type matching the type of `x`, and a result location of `&x`.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] For many syntactic forms of `e`, this has no practical impact.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] However, it can have important semantic effects when working with more complex syntax forms.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] For instance, if the expression `.{ .a = x, .b = y }` has a result location of `ptr`, then `x` is given a result location of `&ptr.a`, and `y` a result location of `&ptr.b`.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Without this system, this expression would construct a temporary struct value entirely on the stack, and only then copy it to the destination address.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] In essence, Zig desugars the assignment `foo = .{ .a = x, .b = y }` to the two statements `foo.a = x; foo.b = y;`.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This can sometimes be important when assigning an aggregate value where the initialization expression depends on the previous value of the aggregate.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] The following table details how some common expressions propagate result locations, where `x` and `y` are arbitrary sub-expressions.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Note that some expressions cannot provide meaningful result locations to sub-expressions, even if they themselves have a result location.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Zig places importance on the concept of whether an expression is known at compile-time.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] There are a few different places this concept is used, and these building blocks are used to keep the language small, readable, and powerful.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Compile-time parameters is how Zig implements generics.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] They can be assigned to variables, passed as parameters to functions, and returned from functions.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] However, they can only be used in expressions which are known at *compile-time*, which is why the parameter `T` in the above snippet must be marked with `comptime`.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This is an error because the programmer attempted to pass a value only known at run-time to a function which expects a value known at compile-time.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Another way to get an error is if we pass a type that violates the type checker when the function is analyzed.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This is what it means to have *compile-time duck typing*.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] On the flip side, inside the function definition with the `comptime` parameter, the value is known at compile-time.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This works because Zig implicitly inlines `if` expressions when the condition is known at compile-time, and the compiler guarantees that it will skip analysis of the branch not taken.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] All the code that dealt with compile-time known values is eliminated and we are left with only the necessary run-time code to accomplish the task.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This works the same way for `switch` expressions - they are implicitly inlined when the target expression is compile-time known.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] In Zig, the programmer can label variables as `comptime`.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This guarantees to the compiler that every load and store of the variable is performed at compile-time.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Any violation of this results in a compile error.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This combined with the fact that we can `inline` loops allows us to write a function which is partially evaluated at compile-time and partially at run-time.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This example is a bit contrived, because the compile-time evaluation component is unnecessary; this code would work fine if it was all done at run-time.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] But it does end up generating different code.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Note that this happens even in a debug build.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This is not a way to write more optimized code, but it is a way to make sure that what *should* happen at compile-time, *does* happen at compile-time.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This catches more errors and allows expressiveness that in other languages requires using macros, generated code, or a preprocessor to accomplish.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] In Zig, it matters whether a given expression is known at compile-time or run-time.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] A programmer can use a `comptime` expression to guarantee that the expression will be evaluated at compile-time.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] If this cannot be accomplished, the compiler will emit an error.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] It doesn't make sense that a program could call `exit()` (or any other external function) at compile-time, so this is a compile error.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] However, a `comptime` expression does much more than sometimes cause a compile error.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This means that a programmer can create a function which is called both at compile-time and run-time, with no modification to the function required.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] The compiler produces an error which is a stack trace from trying to evaluate the function at compile-time.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Luckily, we used an unsigned integer, and so when we tried to subtract 1 from 0, it triggered Illegal Behavior, which is always a compile error if the compiler knows it happened.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] But what would have happened if we used a signed integer?
[src:zig/documentation-p05] The compiler is supposed to notice that evaluating this function at compile-time took more than 1000 branches, and thus emits an error and gives up.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] If the programmer wants to increase the budget for compile-time computation, they can use a built-in function called @setEvalBranchQuota to change the default number 1000 to something else.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] However, there is a design flaw in the compiler causing it to stack overflow instead of having the proper behavior here.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] I hope to get this resolved before the next release.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] What if we fix the base case, but put the wrong value in the `expect` line?
[src:zig/documentation-p05] At Namespace level (outside of any function), all expressions are implicitly `comptime` expressions.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This means that we can use functions to initialize complex constant data.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] When we compile this program, Zig generates the constants with the answer pre-computed.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Note that we did not have to do anything special with the syntax of these functions.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] For example, we could call the `sum` function as is with a slice of numbers whose length and values were only known at run-time.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Zig uses comptime capabilities to implement generic data structures without introducing any special-case syntax.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Here is an example of a generic `List` data structure.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] It's a function that returns an anonymous `struct`.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] For the purposes of error messages and debugging, Zig infers the name `"List(i32)"` from the function name and parameters invoked when creating the anonymous struct.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] To explicitly give a type a name, we assign it to a constant.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] In this example, the `Node` struct refers to itself.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This works because all top level declarations are order-independent.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] As long as the compiler can determine the size of the struct, it is free to refer to itself.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] In this case, `Node` refers to itself as a pointer, which has a well-defined size at compile time, so it works fine.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Putting all of this together, let's see how `print` works in Zig.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This is a proof of concept implementation; the actual function in the standard library has more formatting capabilities.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Note that this is not hard-coded into the Zig compiler; this is userland code in the standard library.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] And now, what happens if we give too many arguments to `print`?
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Zig gives programmers the tools needed to protect themselves against their own mistakes.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Zig does not special case string formatting in the compiler and instead exposes enough power to accomplish this task in userland.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] It does so without introducing another language on top of Zig, such as a macro language or a preprocessor language.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] For some use cases, it may be necessary to directly control the machine code generated by Zig programs, rather than relying on Zig's code generation.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] For these cases, one can use inline assembly.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] For x86 and x86_64 targets, the syntax is AT&T syntax, rather than the more popular Intel syntax.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This is due to technical constraints; assembly parsing is provided by LLVM and its support for Intel syntax is buggy and not well tested.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Some day Zig may have its own assembler.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This would allow it to integrate more seamlessly into the language, as well as be compatible with the popular NASM syntax.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This documentation section will be updated before 1.0.0 is released, with a conclusive statement about the status of AT&T vs Intel/NASM syntax.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Output constraints are still considered to be unstable in Zig, and so LLVM documentation and GCC documentation must be used to understand the semantics.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Note that some breaking changes to output constraints are planned with issue #215.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Input constraints are still considered to be unstable in Zig, and so LLVM documentation and GCC documentation must be used to understand the semantics.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Note that some breaking changes to input constraints are planned with issue #215.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Clobbers are the set of registers whose values will not be preserved by the execution of the assembly code.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] These do not include output or input registers.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] The special clobber value of `"memory"` means that the assembly causes writes to arbitrary undeclared memory locations - not only the memory pointed to by a declared indirect output.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Failure to declare the full set of clobbers for a given inline assembly expression is unchecked Illegal Behavior.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] When an assembly expression occurs in a Namespace level comptime block, this is **global assembly**.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] This kind of assembly has different rules than inline assembly.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] First, `volatile` is not valid because all global assembly is unconditionally included.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Second, there are no inputs, outputs, or clobbers.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] All global assembly is concatenated verbatim into one long string and assembled together.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] There are no template substitution rules regarding `%` as there are in inline assembly expressions.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] Async functions regressed with the release of 0.11.0.
[src:zig/documentation-p05] The current plan is to reintroduce them as a lower level primitive that powers I/O implementations.
[src:zig/documentation-p06] Builtin functions are provided by the compiler and are prefixed with `@`.
