[src:zig/documentation-p08] Many operations in Zig trigger what is known as "Illegal Behavior" (IB).
[src:zig/documentation-p08] If Illegal Behavior is detected at compile-time, Zig emits a compile error and refuses to continue.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Otherwise, when Illegal Behavior is not caught at compile-time, it falls into one of two categories.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Some Illegal Behavior is *safety-checked*: this means that the compiler will insert "safety checks" anywhere that the Illegal Behavior may occur at runtime, to determine whether it is about to happen.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] If it is, the safety check "fails", which triggers a panic.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] All other Illegal Behavior is *unchecked*, meaning the compiler is unable to insert safety checks for it.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] If Unchecked Illegal Behavior is invoked at runtime, anything can happen: usually that will be some kind of crash, but the optimizer is free to make Unchecked Illegal Behavior do anything, such as calling arbitrary functions or clobbering arbitrary data.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] This is similar to the concept of "undefined behavior" in some other languages.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Note that Unchecked Illegal Behavior still always results in a compile error if evaluated at comptime, because the Zig compiler is able to perform more sophisticated checks at compile-time than at runtime.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Most Illegal Behavior is safety-checked.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] However, to facilitate optimizations, safety checks are disabled by default in the ReleaseFast and ReleaseSmall optimization modes.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Safety checks can also be enabled or disabled on a per-block basis, overriding the default for the current optimization mode, using @setRuntimeSafety.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] When safety checks are disabled, Safety-Checked Illegal Behavior behaves like Unchecked Illegal Behavior; that is, any behavior may result from invoking it.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] To obtain the maximum value of an unsigned integer, use `std.math.maxInt`.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] These functions provided by the standard library return possible errors.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] These operations have guaranteed wraparound semantics.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] This safety is not available for `extern` or `packed` unions.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] This happens when casting a float to an integer where the float has a value outside the integer type's range.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] This happens when casting a pointer with the address 0 to a pointer which may not have the address 0.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] For example, C Pointers, Optional Pointers, and allowzero pointers allow address zero, but normal Pointers do not.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] The Zig language performs no memory management on behalf of the programmer.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] This is why Zig has no runtime, and why Zig code works seamlessly in so many environments, including real-time software, operating system kernels, embedded devices, and low latency servers.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Like Zig, the C programming language has manual memory management.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] However, unlike Zig, C has a default allocator - `malloc`, `realloc`, and `free`.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] When linking against libc, Zig exposes this allocator with `std.heap.c_allocator`.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] However, by convention, there is no default allocator in Zig.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Instead, functions which need to allocate accept an `Allocator` parameter.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] In the above example, 100 bytes of stack memory are used to initialize a `FixedBufferAllocator`, which is then passed to a function.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] As a convenience there is a global `FixedBufferAllocator` available for quick tests at `std.testing.allocator`, which will also perform basic leak detection.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Zig has a general purpose allocator available to be imported with `std.heap.DebugAllocator`.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] However, it is still recommended to follow the Choosing an Allocator guide.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] What allocator to use depends on a number of factors.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] In this case, `std.heap.c_allocator` is likely the right choice, at least for your main allocator.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Is the maximum number of bytes that you will need bounded by a number known at comptime?
[src:zig/documentation-p08] In this case, use `std.heap.FixedBufferAllocator`.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Is your program a command line application which runs from start to end without any fundamental cyclical pattern (such as a video game main loop, or a web server request handler), such that it would make sense to free everything at once at the end?
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Everything gets freed at once with the call to `arena.deinit()`.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Are the allocations part of a cyclical pattern such as a video game main loop, or a web server request handler?
[src:zig/documentation-p08] If the allocations can all be freed at once, at the end of the cycle, for example once the video game frame has been fully rendered, or the web server request has been served, then `std.heap.ArenaAllocator` is a great candidate.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] As demonstrated in the previous bullet point, this allows you to free entire arenas at once.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Note also that if an upper bound of memory can be established, then `std.heap.FixedBufferAllocator` can be used as a further optimization.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Are you writing a test, and you want to make sure `error.OutOfMemory` is handled correctly?
[src:zig/documentation-p08] In this case, use `std.testing.FailingAllocator`.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] In this case, use `std.testing.allocator`.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Finally, if none of the above apply, you need a general purpose allocator.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] If you are in Debug mode, `std.heap.DebugAllocator` is available as a function that takes a comptime struct of configuration options and returns a type.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Generally, you will set up exactly one in your main function, and then pass it or sub-allocators around to various parts of your application.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] If you are compiling in ReleaseFast mode, `std.heap.smp_allocator` is a solid choice for a general purpose allocator.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] You can also consider implementing an allocator.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] String literals such as `"hello"` are in the global constant data section.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Just like string literals, `const` declarations, when the value is known at comptime, are stored in the global constant data section.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Also Compile Time Variables are stored in the global constant data section.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] `var` declarations inside functions are stored in the function's stack frame.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Once a function returns, any Pointers to variables in the function's stack frame become invalid references, and dereferencing them becomes unchecked Illegal Behavior.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] `var` declarations at the top level or in struct declarations are stored in the global data section.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] The location of memory allocated with `allocator.alloc` or `allocator.create` is determined by the allocator's implementation.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Many programming languages choose to handle the possibility of heap allocation failure by unconditionally crashing.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] By convention, Zig programmers do not consider this to be a satisfactory solution.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Instead, `error.OutOfMemory` represents heap allocation failure, and Zig libraries return this error code whenever heap allocation failure prevented an operation from completing successfully.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Some have argued that because some operating systems such as Linux have memory overcommit enabled by default, it is pointless to handle heap allocation failure.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Recursion is a fundamental tool in modeling software.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] However it has an often-overlooked problem: unbounded memory allocation.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Recursion is an area of active experimentation in Zig and so the documentation here is not final.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] You can read a summary of recursion status in the 0.3.0 release notes.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] The short summary is that currently recursion works normally as you would expect.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Although Zig code is not yet protected from stack overflow, it is planned that a future version of Zig will provide such protection, with some degree of cooperation from Zig code required.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] It is the Zig programmer's responsibility to ensure that a pointer is not accessed when the memory pointed to is no longer available.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Note that a slice is a form of pointer, in that it references other memory.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] In order to prevent bugs, there are some helpful conventions to follow when dealing with pointers.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] In general, when a function returns a pointer, the documentation for the function should explain who "owns" the pointer.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] This concept helps the programmer decide when it is appropriate, if ever, to free the pointer.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] For example, the function's documentation may say "caller owns the returned memory", in which case the code that calls the function must have a plan for when to free that memory.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Probably in this situation, the function will accept an `Allocator` parameter.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Sometimes the lifetime of a pointer may be more complicated.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] For example, the `std.ArrayList(T).items` slice has a lifetime that remains valid until the next time the list is resized, such as by appending new elements.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] The API documentation for functions and data structures should take great care to explain the ownership and lifetime semantics of pointers.
[src:zig/documentation-p08] Ownership determines whose responsibility it is to free the memory referenced by the pointer, and lifetime determines the point at which the memory becomes inaccessible (lest Illegal Behavior occur).
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Compile variables are accessible by importing the `"builtin"` package, which the compiler makes available to every Zig source file.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] It contains compile-time constants such as the current target, endianness, and release mode.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] A Zig compilation is separated into *modules*.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Each module is a collection of Zig source files, one of which is the module's *root source file*.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Each module can *depend* on any number of other modules, forming a directed graph (dependency loops between modules are allowed).
[src:zig/documentation-p09] If module A depends on module B, then any Zig source file in module A can import the *root source file* of module B using `@import` with the module's name.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] In essence, a module acts as an alias to import a Zig source file (which might exist in a completely separate part of the filesystem).
[src:zig/documentation-p09] A simple Zig program compiled with `zig build-exe` has two key modules: the one containing your code, known as the "main" or "root" module, and the standard library.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Your module *depends on* the standard library module under the name "std", which is what allows you to write `@import("std")`!
[src:zig/documentation-p09] In fact, every single module in a Zig compilation — including the standard library itself — implicitly depends on the standard library module under the name "std".
[src:zig/documentation-p09] The "root module" (the one provided by you in the `zig build-exe` example) has a special property.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Like the standard library, it is implicitly made available to all modules (including itself), this time under the name "root".
[src:zig/documentation-p09] So, `@import("root")` will always be equivalent to `@import` of your "main" source file (often, but not necessarily, named `main.zig`).
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Every Zig source file is implicitly a `struct` declaration; you can imagine that the file's contents are literally surrounded by `struct { ... }`.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Such files can be instantiated just like any other `struct` type.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] A file's "root struct type" can be referred to within that file using @This.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Zig places importance on the concept of whether any piece of code is *semantically analyzed*; in essence, whether the compiler "looks at" it.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] What code is analyzed is based on what files and declarations are "discovered" from a certain point.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Those rules define how Zig files and declarations are discovered.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] All that remains is to understand where this process *starts*.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] The answer to that is the root of the standard library: every Zig compilation begins by analyzing the file `lib/std/std.zig`.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] It is often desirable to make sure that certain declarations — particularly `test` or `export` declarations — are discovered.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Because the root module's root source file is always accessible using `@import("root")`, is is sometimes used by libraries — including the Zig Standard Library — as a place for the program to expose some "global" information to that library.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] The Zig Standard Library will look for several declarations in this file.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] When building an executable, the most important thing to be looked up in this file is the program's *entry point*.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Most commonly, this is a function named `main`, which `std.start` will call just after performing important initialization work.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Alternatively, the presence of a declaration named `_start` (for instance, `pub const _start = {};`) will disable the default `std.start` logic, allowing your root source file to export a low-level entry point as needed.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] `std.start` may also use other entry point declarations in certain situations, such as `wWinMain` or `EfiMain`.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Refer to the `lib/std/start.zig` logic for details of these declarations.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] The standard library also looks for a declaration in the root module's root source file named `std_options`.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] If present, this declaration is expected to be a struct of type `std.Options`, and allows the program to customize some standard library functionality, such as the `std.log` implementation.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] The Zig Standard Library looks for a declaration named `panic` in the root module's root source file.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] If present, it is expected to be a Namespace with declarations providing different panic handlers.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] See `std.debug.simple_panic` for a basic implementation of this namespace.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] The Zig Build System provides a cross-platform, dependency-free way to declare the logic required to build a project.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] With this system, the logic to build a project is written in a build.zig file, using the Zig Build System API to declare and configure build artifacts and other tasks.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] To use the build system, run zig build --help to see a command-line usage help menu.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] This will include project-specific options that were declared in the build.zig script.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Although Zig is independent of C, and, unlike most other languages, does not depend on libc, Zig acknowledges the importance of interacting with existing C code.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] There are a few ways that Zig facilitates C interop.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] These have guaranteed C ABI compatibility and can be used like any other type.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] To interop with the C `void` type, use `anyopaque`.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Zig's C translation capability is available as a CLI tool via zig translate-c.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] It requires a single filename as an argument.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] It may also take a set of optional flags that are forwarded to clang.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] It writes the translated file to stdout.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Some C constructs cannot be translated to Zig - for example, *goto*, structs with bitfields, and token-pasting macros.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Zig employs *demotion* to allow translation to continue in the face of non-translatable entities.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Demotion comes in three varieties - opaque, *extern*, and `@compileError`.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] C structs and unions that cannot be translated correctly will be translated as `opaque{}`.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Functions that contain opaque types or code constructs that cannot be translated will be demoted to `extern` declarations.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Thus, non-translatable types can still be used as pointers, and non-translatable functions can be called so long as the linker is aware of the compiled function.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] `@compileError` is used when top-level definitions (global variables, function prototypes, macros) cannot be translated or demoted.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Since Zig uses lazy analysis for top-level declarations, untranslatable entities will not cause a compile error in your code unless you actually use them.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] This type is to be avoided whenever possible.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] The only valid reason for using a C pointer is in auto-generated code from translating C code.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] When importing C header files, it is ambiguous whether pointers should be translated as single-item pointers (`*T`) or many-item pointers (`[*]T`).
[src:zig/documentation-p09] C pointers are a compromise so that Zig code can utilize translated header files directly.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] When a C pointer is pointing to a single struct (not an array), dereference the C pointer to access the struct's fields or member data.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Variadic functions can be implemented using @cVaStart, @cVaEnd, @cVaArg and @cVaCopy.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] One of the primary use cases for Zig is exporting a library with the C ABI for other programming languages to call into.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] You can mix Zig object files with any other object files that respect the C ABI.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Zig supports building for WebAssembly out of the box.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] For host environments like the web browser and nodejs, build as an executable using the freestanding OS target.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Here's an example of running Zig code compiled to WebAssembly with nodejs.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Zig standard library has first-class support for WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] A more interesting example would be extracting the list of preopens from the runtime.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Zig is a general-purpose programming language which means that it is designed to generate optimal code for a large set of targets.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] The command `zig targets` provides information about all of the targets the compiler is aware of.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] When no target option is provided to the compiler, the default choice is to target the **host computer**, meaning that the resulting executable will be *unsuitable for copying to a different computer*.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] In order to copy an executable to another computer, the compiler needs to know about the target requirements via the `-target` option.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] The Zig Standard Library (`@import("std")`) has cross-platform abstractions, making the same source code viable on many targets.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Some code is more portable than other code.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] In general, Zig code is extremely portable compared to other programming languages.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Each platform requires its own implementations to make Zig's cross-platform abstractions work.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] These implementations are at various degrees of completion.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Each tagged release of the compiler comes with release notes that provide the full support table for each target.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] These coding conventions are not enforced by the compiler, but they are shipped in this documentation along with the compiler in order to provide a point of reference, should anyone wish to point to an authority on agreed upon Zig coding style.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Everything is a value, all types are data, everything is context, all logic manages state.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Nothing is communicated by using a word that applies to all types.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Temptation to use "utilities", "miscellaneous", or somebody's initials is a failure to categorize, or more commonly, overcategorization.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Such declarations can live at the root of a module that needs them with no namespace needed.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Every declaration is assigned a **fully qualified namespace** by the compiler, creating a tree structure.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Choose names based on the fully-qualified namespace, and avoid redundant name segments.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] In this example, "json" is repeated in the fully-qualified namespace.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] The solution is to delete `Json` from `JsonValue`.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] In this example we have an empty struct named `json` but remember that files also act as part of the fully-qualified namespace.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] This example is an exception to the rule specified in Avoid Redundancy in Names.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] The meaning of the type has been reduced to its core: it is a json value.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] The name cannot be any more specific without being incorrect.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] In Zig, there are no private fields, and this style guide recommends against pretending otherwise.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Instead, fields should be named carefully based on their semantics and documentation should indicate how to use fields without violating data invariants.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] If a field is not subject to the same semantic versioning rules as everything else, the exception should be noted in the Doc Comments.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] As for type reflection, it is less error prone and more maintainable to use the type system than to make field names meaningful.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Regarding name collisions, an underscore is insufficient to explain the difference between the two otherwise identical names.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] If there's no danger in getting them mixed up, then this guide recommends more verbose names at outer scopes and more abbreviated names at inner scopes.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Finally, keyword collisions are better avoided via String Identifier Syntax.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Roughly speaking: `camelCaseFunctionName`, `TitleCaseTypeName`, `snake_case_variable_name`.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Acronyms, initialisms, proper nouns, or any other word that has capitalization rules in written English are subject to naming conventions just like any other word.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Even acronyms that are only 2 letters long are subject to these conventions.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] File names fall into two categories: types and namespaces.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] If the file (implicitly a struct) has top level fields, it should be named like any other struct with fields using `TitleCase`.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] These are general rules of thumb; if it makes sense to do something different, do what makes sense.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] For example, if there is an established convention such as `ENOENT`, follow the established convention.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] See the Zig Standard Library for more examples.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] An invalid UTF-8 byte sequence results in a compile error.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] LF (byte value 0x0a, code point U+000a, `'\n'`) is the line terminator in Zig source code.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] This byte value terminates every line of zig source code except the last line of the file.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] It is recommended that non-empty source files end with an empty line, which means the last byte would be 0x0a (LF).
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Each LF may be immediately preceded by a single CR (byte value 0x0d, code point U+000d, `'\r'`) to form a Windows style line ending, but this is discouraged.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Note that in multiline strings, CRLF sequences will be encoded as LF when compiled into a zig program.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] A CR in any other context is not allowed.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] HT hard tabs (byte value 0x09, code point U+0009, `'\t'`) are interchangeable with SP spaces (byte value 0x20, code point U+0020, `' '`) as a token separator, but use of hard tabs is discouraged.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] For compatibility with other tools, the compiler ignores a UTF-8-encoded byte order mark (U+FEFF) if it is the first Unicode code point in the source text.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] A byte order mark is not allowed anywhere else in the source.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Note that running zig fmt on a source file will implement all recommendations mentioned here.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] Note that a tool reading Zig source code can make assumptions if the source code is assumed to be correct Zig code.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] For example, when identifying the ends of lines, a tool can use a naive search such as `/\n/`, or an advanced search such as `/\r\n?|[\n\u0085\u2028\u2029]/`, and in either case line endings will be correctly identified.
[src:zig/documentation-p09] For another example, when identifying the whitespace before the first token on a line, a tool can either use a naive search such as `/[ \t]/`, or an advanced search such as `/\s/`, and in either case whitespace will be correctly identified.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Focus on debugging your application rather than debugging your programming language knowledge.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Zig’s entire syntax is specified with a 580-line PEG grammar file.
[src:zig/learn-overview] There is **no hidden control flow**, no hidden memory allocations, no preprocessor, and no macros.
[src:zig/learn-overview] If Zig code doesn’t look like it’s jumping away to call a function, then it isn’t.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Zig promotes code maintenance and readability by making all control flow managed exclusively with language keywords and function calls.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Zig has four build modes, and they can all be mixed and matched all the way down to scope granularity.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Those stack traces work on all targets, including freestanding.
[src:zig/learn-overview] With Zig one can rely on a safety-enabled build mode, and selectively disable safety at the performance bottlenecks.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Zig uses Illegal Behavior as a razor sharp tool for both bug prevention and performance enhancement.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Speaking of performance, Zig is faster than C.
[src:zig/learn-overview] The Zig Standard Library integrates with libc, but does not depend on it.
[src:zig/learn-overview] `const std = @import("std"); pub fn main() void { std.debug.print("Hello, world!\n", .{}); }`$ zig build-exe 4-hello.zig $ ./4-hello Hello, world!
[src:zig/learn-overview] Top level declarations such as global variables are order-independent and lazily analyzed.
[src:zig/learn-overview] The initialization values of global variables are evaluated at compile-time.
[src:zig/learn-overview] In other programming languages, null references are the source of many runtime exceptions, and even stand accused of being the worst mistake of computer science.
[src:zig/learn-overview] `const std = @import("std"); const assert = std.debug.assert; test "null @intToPtr" { const ptr: ?*i32 = @ptrFromInt(0x0); assert(ptr == null); }`$ zig test 7-optional-syntax.zig 1/1 7-optional-syntax.test.null @intToPtr...OK All 1 tests passed.
[src:zig/learn-overview] In order to accomplish this, Zig programmers must manage their own memory, and must handle memory allocation failure.
[src:zig/learn-overview] This is true of the Zig Standard Library as well.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Any functions that need to allocate memory accept an allocator parameter.
[src:zig/learn-overview] As a result, the Zig Standard Library can be used even for the freestanding target.
[src:zig/learn-overview] In addition to A fresh take on error handling, Zig provides defer and errdefer to make all resource management - not only memory - simple and easily verifiable.
[src:zig/learn-overview] For an example of `defer`, see Integration with C libraries without FFI/bindings.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Note that is an Error Return Trace, not a stack trace.
[src:zig/learn-overview] The code did not pay the price of unwinding the stack to come up with that trace.
[src:zig/learn-overview] This invokes undefined behavior in the unsafe build modes, so be sure to use it only when success is guaranteed.
[src:zig/learn-overview] The stack traces and error return traces shown on this page work on all Tier 1 Support and some Tier 2 Support targets.
[src:zig/learn-overview] The standard library’s DebugAllocator uses this technique to report leaks and double frees.
[src:zig/learn-overview] `const std = @import("std"); const assert = std.debug.assert; test "types are values" { const T1 = u8; const T2 = bool; assert(T1 != T2); const x: T2 = true; assert(x); }`$ zig test 18-types.zig 1/1 18-types.test.types are values...OK All 1 tests passed.
[src:zig/learn-overview] The Zig Standard Library uses this technique to implement formatted printing.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Despite being a Small, simple language, Zig’s formatted printing is implemented entirely in Zig.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Meanwhile, in C, compile errors for printf are hard-coded into the compiler.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Similarly, in Rust, the formatted printing macro is hard-coded into the compiler.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Zig can also evaluate functions and blocks of code at compile-time.
[src:zig/learn-overview] In some contexts, such as global variable initializations, the expression is implicitly evaluated at compile-time.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Otherwise, one can explicitly evaluate code at compile-time with the comptime keyword.
[src:zig/learn-overview] @cImport directly imports types, variables, functions, and simple macros for use in Zig.
[src:zig/learn-overview] It even translates inline functions from C into Zig.
[src:zig/learn-overview] This Zig code is significantly simpler than the equivalent C code, as well as having more safety protections, and all this is accomplished by directly importing the C header file - no API bindings.
[src:zig/learn-overview] This is thanks to Build Artifact Caching.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Zig automatically parses the .d file using a robust caching system to avoid duplicating work.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Not only can Zig compile C code, but there is a very good reason to use Zig as a C compiler: Zig ships with libc.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Zig builds for all supported targets independently of the host.
[src:zig/learn-overview] There is no separate “cross toolchain” or anything like that.
[src:zig/learn-overview] This works on any Tier 3+ target, for any Tier 3+ target.
[src:zig/learn-overview] This means `-lc` for these targets *does not depend on any system files*!
[src:zig/learn-overview] In this example, Zig built musl libc from source and then linked against it.
[src:zig/learn-overview] The build of musl libc for x86_64-linux remains available thanks to the caching system, so any time this libc is needed again it will be available instantly.
[src:zig/learn-overview] This means that this functionality is available on any platform.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Windows and macOS users can build Zig and C code, and link against libc, for any of the targets listed above.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Zig is a better C compiler than C compilers!
[src:zig/learn-overview] This functionality is more than bundling a cross-compilation toolchain along with Zig.
[src:zig/learn-overview] For example, the total size of libc headers that Zig ships is 130 MiB uncompressed.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Meanwhile, the headers for musl libc + linux headers on x86_64 alone are 8 MiB, and for glibc are 3.1 MiB (glibc is missing the linux headers), yet Zig currently ships with 97 libcs.
[src:zig/learn-overview] With a naive bundling that would be 776 MiB.
[src:zig/learn-overview] However, thanks to this process_headers tool, and some good old manual labor, Zig binary tarballs remain roughly 50 MiB total, despite supporting libc for all these targets, as well as compiler-rt, libunwind, libcxx, and libtsan, and despite being a clang-compatible C compiler.
[src:zig/learn-overview] For comparison, the Windows binary build of clang 8.0.0 itself from llvm.org is 132 MiB.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Zig comes with a build system, so you don’t need a separate tool to orchestrate your build process.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Let’s have a look at that `--help` menu.
[src:zig/learn-overview] You can see that one of the available steps is run.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Zig uses a “support tier” system to communicate the level of support for different targets.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Even though Zig is self-hosted, building from source only depends on system C/C++ toolchain and LLVM, using standard CMake build steps thanks to a WebAssembly based bootstrap process.
[src:zig/learn-overview] For those distributions that want to avoid binary blobs, there is a well-documented set of steps to reproduce Zig without binaries.
[src:zig/learn-overview] In the future, we hope to inspire a third party to implement a Zig interpreter written in C that can reduce this to O(1) step.
[src:zig/learn-overview] The build system acknowledges system integration as an explicit intent.
[src:zig/learn-overview] For example, the `--system <path>` flag disables package fetching and enables all `-fsys=[name]` options.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Those “system integration options” are available in build scripts, allowing package maintainers and upstream developers to cooperate.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Fewer patches for package maintainers, and upstream authors can make intentional choices in response to system integration build configuration.
[src:zig/learn-overview] Non-debug build modes are reproducible/deterministic.
[src:zig/learn-overview] There is a JSON version of the download page.
